  "reason_thou": "### 1.
Understanding the
Issue\nThe issue arises
from the
`GVNSink::sinkLastInstruc
tion` function,
specifically when
creating a new `PHINode`
for operands that differ
across the instructions
being sunk. The
`PHINode::Create`
function is invoked to
create a new `PHINode` in
the successor block, but
the code does not account
for the possibility of
invalid IR being
generated when the
operands include inline
assembly instructions.
Inline assembly
instructions cannot be
used as operands in a
`PHINode`, as they do not
have a valid
address.\n\n### 2.
Analyzing `opt`'s
Log\nThe log indicates
that the `gvn-sink` pass
attempts to sink
instructions and creates
a `PHINode` with operands
that include inline
assembly. This results in
the error: `Cannot take
the address of an inline
asm!`. The `PHINode`
creation is invalid
because inline assembly
instructions cannot be
used as operands in a
`PHINode`.\n\n### 3. Root
Cause Analysis\nThe
`GVNSink` pass attempts
to sink instructions and
create `PHINode`s for
operands that differ
across the instructions
being sunk. However, when
the operands include
inline assembly
instructions, the
`PHINode` creation leads
to invalid IR because
inline assembly
instructions cannot be
used as operands in a
`PHINode`.\n\n### 4.
Proposed Edit
Points\n**File**:
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Scal
ar/GVNSink.cpp`\n**Lines*
*: Around 807-823 (inside
the loop iterating over
operands in
`GVNSink::sinkLastInstruc
tion`).\n\n### Fix
Implementation\nAdd a
check to skip sinking if
any operand is an inline
assembly
instruction:\n```cpp\nif
(isa<InlineAsm>(Op)) {\n
LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() <<
\"GVNSink: Skipping
sinking due to inline
assembly operand\\n\");\n
return;\n}\n```\n\n### 5.
Conclusion\nThis fix
ensures that the
`GVNSink` pass does not
attempt to sink
instructions with
operands that include
inline assembly, thereby
preventing the generation
of invalid IR and
avoiding the crash. The
added check is
lightweight and only
affects cases involving
inline assembly, so it
should not impact the
performance or
correctness of the pass
in other scenarios.",
